{
  "A primary battery is one that:": "",
  "Uses only liquid electrolytes": "",
  "Produces alternating current": "",
  "Cannot be recharged; the reaction is irreversible": "",
  "Can be recharged many times": "",
  "A primary battery (or cell) cannot be recharged because the electrochemical reactions are not easily reversible. Once the reactants are consumed, the battery is dead. Common examples include alkaline batteries and zinc-carbon batteries.": "",
  "A secondary battery differs from a primary battery because it:": "",
  "Is larger in size when considering all relevant battery factors": "",
  "Can be recharged by applying an external voltage to reverse the reaction": "",
  "Uses solid electrolytes only, even when conditions shift": "",
  "Produces a higher voltage, especially during periods": "",
  "A secondary (rechargeable) battery can be recharged by applying an external electrical current that reverses the chemical reaction. This converts the cell from galvanic mode to electrolytic mode during charging. Examples include lithium-ion, lead-acid, and nickel-metal hydride batteries.": "",
  "In a lead-acid battery, what serves as the anode?": "",
  "Pb (lead metal)": "",
  "PbSO4, which": "",
  "H2SO4 without": "",
  "PbO2 when": "",
  "In a lead-acid battery, lead metal (Pb) is the anode, where it is oxidized: Pb + SO4^2- -> PbSO4 + 2e-. Lead dioxide (PbO2) serves as the cathode, where it is reduced: PbO2 + 4H+ + SO4^2- + 2e- -> PbSO4 + 2H2O.": "",
  "What is the electrolyte in a standard alkaline battery?": "",
  "Lithium chloride": "",
  "Potassium hydroxide (KOH)": "",
  "Sulfuric acid": "",
  "Sodium chloride": "",
  "Alkaline batteries use potassium hydroxide (KOH) as the electrolyte, which is why they are called 'alkaline.' The anode is zinc powder and the cathode is manganese dioxide (MnO2). The basic electrolyte allows higher energy density than zinc-carbon batteries.": "",
  "Corrosion of iron (rusting) requires the presence of:": "",
  "Both oxygen and water": "",
  "Only oxygen": "",
  "Only water": "",
  "Only acidic conditions": "",
  "Iron corrosion (rusting) requires both oxygen and water (moisture). Iron is oxidized at anodic sites: Fe -> Fe2+ + 2e-, while oxygen is reduced at cathodic sites: O2 + 2H2O + 4e- -> 4OH-. The Fe2+ and OH- combine to eventually form Fe2O3 (rust).": "",
  "The voltage of a single cell in a lead-acid battery is approximately:": "",
  "2.0 V": "",
  "1.5 V": "",
  "3.7 V": "",
  "12.0 V": "",
  "Each cell in a lead-acid battery produces approximately 2.0 V. A standard 12 V car battery consists of six cells connected in series (6 x 2.0 = 12 V). The overall reaction is Pb + PbO2 + 2H2SO4 -> 2PbSO4 + 2H2O.": "",
  "Galvanizing is a corrosion prevention method that involves:": "",
  "Alloying iron with gold": "",
  "Coating iron with a layer of copper": "",
  "Painting iron with acid-resistant paint": "",
  "Coating iron with a layer of zinc": "",
  "Galvanizing involves coating iron or steel with zinc. Zinc is more reactive (more easily oxidized) than iron, so even if the coating is scratched, the zinc corrodes preferentially (acts as a sacrificial anode), protecting the underlying iron.": "",
  "A fuel cell differs from a battery because it:": "",
  "Does not involve redox reactions": "",
  "Continuously converts fuel supplied from outside into electricity": "",
  "Can only operate at high temperatures": "",
  "Stores reactants internally": "",
  "A fuel cell continuously converts chemical energy of an externally supplied fuel (such as hydrogen) and an oxidant (such as oxygen) into electricity. Unlike batteries, fuel cells do not store energy internally; they keep producing electricity as long as fuel is supplied.": "",
  "In a lithium-ion battery, lithium ions move from the anode to the cathode during:": "",
  "Charging": "",
  "Neither; Li+ ions do not move": "",
  "Both charging and discharging": "",
  "Discharging": "",
  "During discharging, lithium ions move from the anode (typically graphite) through the electrolyte to the cathode (typically a lithium metal oxide). During charging, the reverse occurs: Li+ ions move from the cathode back to the anode.": "",
  "Cathodic protection prevents corrosion by:": "",
  "Removing all oxygen from the environment": "",
  "Coating the metal with an insulating layer": "",
  "Heating the metal to drive off moisture": "",
  "Attaching a more reactive metal that corrodes instead (sacrificial anode)": "",
  "Cathodic protection uses a sacrificial anode (a more reactive metal like zinc or magnesium) that is preferentially oxidized instead of the protected metal. The protected metal becomes the cathode, where only reduction occurs, preventing its corrosion.": "",
  "What does the term 'primary cell' mean?": "",
  "An electrochemical cell whose reaction is irreversible, making it non-rechargeable": "",
  "A cell that provides primary power to a grid": "",
  "The first cell in a series of cells": "",
  "A cell with the highest voltage": "",
  "A primary cell is a non-rechargeable electrochemical cell. The chemical reactions that generate electricity are irreversible, meaning the original reactants cannot be regenerated by applying an external current. Once the reactants are depleted, the cell must be discarded.": "",
  "What does the term 'secondary cell' mean?": "",
  "A backup cell in case the primary fails": "",
  "A cell with lower voltage than a primary cell": "",
  "A rechargeable electrochemical cell whose reaction can be reversed by applying an external current": "",
  "A cell that uses a secondary electrolyte": "",
  "A secondary cell (rechargeable battery) uses reversible chemical reactions. Applying external electrical energy forces the reactions to run in reverse, regenerating the original reactants. This allows the cell to be charged and discharged many times.": "",
  "What does the term 'corrosion' mean?": "",
  "The melting of metal at high temperatures": "",
  "The dissolution of metal in acid": "",
  "The gradual destruction of a metal by electrochemical oxidation reactions with substances in the environment": "",
  "The physical wearing away of metal by friction": "",
  "Corrosion is the degradation of a metal through electrochemical oxidation reactions with environmental agents, primarily oxygen and water. It is an electrochemical process with distinct anodic (oxidation) and cathodic (reduction) sites on the metal surface.": "",
  "What does the term 'sacrificial anode' mean?": "",
  "The anode in a primary cell": "",
  "An anode that has been coated with a protective layer": "",
  "An anode that dissolves during electrolysis": "",
  "An anode that is designed to be corroded (oxidized) preferentially to protect another metal": "",
  "A sacrificial anode is a more reactive (more easily oxidized) metal intentionally attached to a less reactive metal to protect it from corrosion. The sacrificial anode corrodes instead, being consumed over time. Examples include zinc blocks on ship hulls and magnesium rods in water heaters.": "",
  "What does the term 'fuel cell' mean?": "",
  "A generator that converts heat directly to electricity": "",
  "A cell that stores fuel for later combustion": "",
  "An electrochemical cell that continuously generates electricity from externally supplied fuel and oxidant": "",
  "A battery powered by gasoline": "",
  "A fuel cell is an electrochemical device that converts chemical energy directly into electrical energy through redox reactions, using externally supplied fuel and oxidant. The most common type is the hydrogen fuel cell: 2H2 + O2 -> 2H2O, producing electricity, water, and heat.": "",
  "What does 'galvanizing' mean?": "",
  "Coating iron or steel with zinc to protect against corrosion": "",
  "Heating metal to improve its conductivity": "",
  "Shocking metal with electricity to harden it": "",
  "Combining two metals to form an alloy": "",
  "Galvanizing is the process of coating iron or steel with zinc, usually by hot-dipping or electroplating. The zinc layer protects the iron both as a physical barrier and through cathodic protection (zinc is oxidized preferentially since it is more reactive than iron).": "",
  "What does 'passivation' mean in corrosion chemistry?": "",
  "The removal of all oxide from a metal surface": "",
  "The process of making a metal more reactive": "",
  "The complete dissolution of a metal in acid": "",
  "The formation of a thin, protective oxide layer on a metal surface that prevents further corrosion": "",
  "Passivation occurs when a metal forms a thin, stable oxide layer on its surface that acts as a barrier, preventing further oxidation. Aluminum, chromium, and stainless steel are examples of metals that passivate effectively, which is why they resist corrosion despite being reactive.": "",
  "What does 'energy density' mean when comparing batteries?": "",
  "The number of cells in the battery": "",
  "How quickly the battery can deliver energy": "",
  "The voltage output of the battery": "",
  "The amount of energy stored per unit mass or volume of the battery": "",
  "Energy density is the amount of energy stored per unit mass (Wh/kg, gravimetric) or per unit volume (Wh/L, volumetric). Lithium-ion batteries have high energy density (~250 Wh/kg), which is why they are preferred for portable electronics and electric vehicles.": "",
  "What does the term 'dry cell' mean?": "",
  "A battery that contains no electrolyte": "",
  "A fuel cell that uses dry hydrogen gas": "",
  "A battery that uses a paste electrolyte rather than a liquid, making it portable and leak-resistant": "",
  "A battery that must be kept in a dry environment": "",
  "A dry cell uses a paste or gel electrolyte instead of a liquid, making it portable and less prone to leaking. The common zinc-carbon and alkaline batteries are dry cells. The term distinguishes them from wet cells like lead-acid batteries that use liquid electrolyte.": "",
  "What does the term 'cell in series' mean for batteries?": "",
  "Cells that can only be used one after another": "",
  "Multiple cells connected positive-to-negative to increase total voltage": "",
  "Multiple cells connected side-by-side to increase current": "",
  "Cells that are manufactured in sequential order": "",
  "When cells are connected in series (positive terminal of one to negative terminal of the next), their voltages add together while the current capacity remains the same as a single cell. A 12 V car battery has six 2 V cells in series.": "",
  "A homeowner notices that the water heater's magnesium anode rod has corroded significantly after 5 years, but the steel tank is intact. This is an example of:": "",
  "Passivation of the magnesium, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Galvanic corrosion where magnesium protects steel by being oxidized preferentially": "",
  "Electrolysis of the water, based on conventional assumptions about": "",
  "A manufacturing defect without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "This is cathodic protection using a sacrificial anode. Magnesium is more reactive than iron/steel (E-standard for Mg2+/Mg = -2.37 V vs Fe2+/Fe = -0.44 V), so it is preferentially oxidized, protecting the steel tank. The magnesium rod needs periodic replacement as it corrodes.": "",
  "A student is comparing a nickel-cadmium (NiCd) battery to a lithium-ion (Li-ion) battery for a portable device. The Li-ion battery has a nominal voltage of 3.7 V per cell and energy density of 250 Wh/kg. The NiCd has 1.2 V per cell and 45 Wh/kg. Why are Li-ion batteries preferred for smartphones?": "",
  "NiCd batteries are cheaper, based on conventional assumptions about battery": "",
  "Li-ion batteries have higher energy density and voltage per cell, allowing lighter, more compact designs": "",
  "NiCd batteries cannot be recharged, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Li-ion batteries last forever under most circumstances involving battery": "",
  "Li-ion batteries have about 5 times the energy density of NiCd (250 vs 45 Wh/kg) and 3 times the voltage per cell (3.7 vs 1.2 V). This means a Li-ion battery can store more energy in less space and weight, which is critical for portable electronic devices.": "",
  "A marine engineer needs to protect an iron ship hull from corrosion in seawater. She attaches zinc blocks to the hull. Using standard reduction potentials (Zn2+/Zn = -0.76 V, Fe2+/Fe = -0.44 V), explain why this works.": "",
  "Zinc absorbs oxygen from the water in most scenarios involving zinc factors": "",
  "Zinc has a more negative reduction potential, so it is oxidized preferentially, making the iron the cathode where only reduction occurs": "",
  "Zinc blocks the water from reaching the iron under most circumstances involving zinc": "",
  "Zinc neutralizes the salt in seawater when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Zinc has a more negative standard reduction potential (-0.76 V) than iron (-0.44 V), meaning zinc is more easily oxidized. When both are in contact in seawater (electrolyte), zinc becomes the anode and corrodes, while iron becomes the cathode where reduction occurs (O2 + 2H2O + 4e- -> 4OH-). The iron is protected as long as zinc remains.": "",
  "A chemistry teacher demonstrates a lemon battery using a copper penny and a zinc nail inserted into a lemon. The cell produces about 0.9 V. If three lemon cells are connected in series, what is the total voltage?": "",
  "2.7 V": "",
  "0.3 V": "",
  "0.9 V": "",
  "8.1 V": "",
  "When cells are connected in series, their voltages add: 0.9 + 0.9 + 0.9 = 2.7 V. The citric acid in the lemon acts as the electrolyte. Zinc is oxidized at the anode (more negative E-standard) and H+ is reduced at the copper cathode.": "",
  "A car battery is rated at 60 Ah (ampere-hours). If the car's starter motor draws 200 A, how long can the battery deliver this current before being completely discharged?": "",
  "3.3 hours": "",
  "12 hours": "",
  "1.0 hour": "",
  "0.3 hours (18 minutes)": "",
  "Time = capacity / current = 60 Ah / 200 A = 0.3 hours = 18 minutes. In practice, the actual time would be less because high discharge rates reduce the effective capacity. The Ah rating tells you how many amperes the battery can deliver for one hour.": "",
  "A researcher studying hydrogen fuel cells notes that the overall reaction is 2H2(g) + O2(g) -> 2H2O(l) with E-cell = +1.23 V. What makes fuel cells more efficient than combustion engines?": "",
  "Fuel cells convert chemical energy directly to electricity without the thermodynamic limitations of heat engines": "",
  "Fuel cells can use any fuel, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Fuel cells use cheaper fuel, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Fuel cells produce more heat, based on conventional assumptions about cells": "",
  "Fuel cells convert chemical energy directly to electrical energy without intermediate heat conversion. Combustion engines are limited by the Carnot efficiency (dependent on temperature differences), typically achieving 25-40% efficiency. Fuel cells can theoretically achieve 80-90% efficiency, though practical values are 40-60%.": "",
  "A bridge inspector notices that iron bolts connecting copper plates have corroded badly, while the copper remains pristine. Using electrochemistry, explain this observation.": "",
  "The copper prevented oxygen from reaching the iron": "",
  "Iron is more easily oxidized than copper (lower reduction potential), so it acts as the anode and corrodes preferentially in the galvanic couple": "",
  "Iron reacted with the copper to form an alloy": "",
  "Copper is a better conductor, so it does not corrode": "",
  "When iron (E = -0.44 V) and copper (E = +0.34 V) are in contact in the presence of moisture, they form a galvanic couple. Iron, with its more negative reduction potential, becomes the anode and corrodes, while copper becomes the cathode and is protected. This is galvanic corrosion and is why dissimilar metals in contact should be avoided.": "",
  "A manufacturing plant uses a lead-acid battery to power a forklift. During charging, the reaction PbSO4 -> Pb and PbSO4 -> PbO2 is driven in reverse. What happens to the H2SO4 concentration during charging?": "",
  "It increases": "",
  "It remains the same": "",
  "It fluctuates randomly": "",
  "It decreases": "",
  "During discharging, H2SO4 is consumed (Pb + PbO2 + 2H2SO4 -> 2PbSO4 + 2H2O). During charging, this reaction is reversed, regenerating H2SO4 from PbSO4 and H2O. Therefore, the acid concentration increases during charging. Mechanics check battery charge by measuring the specific gravity (density) of the acid.": "",
  "An environmental engineer is evaluating corrosion rates of steel pipes in different soils. In which environment would corrosion be fastest?": "",
  "Wet, salty clay soil with high conductivity": "",
  "Pure dry nitrogen atmosphere": "",
  "Dry sandy soil with low conductivity": "",
  "Frozen soil with no moisture": "",
  "Corrosion requires moisture (electrolyte), oxygen, and ionic conductivity. Wet, salty clay soil provides all three: water as the medium, dissolved salts (ions) for electrolyte conductivity, and access to oxygen. Higher salt concentration increases conductivity, accelerating the electrochemical corrosion process.": "",
  "A battery engineer designs a new lithium-ion cell with E-cell = 3.8 V. She connects 4 cells in series and 3 such series strings in parallel. What is the total voltage and how does the current capacity compare to a single cell?": "",
  "15.2 V, triple the current capacity of one cell": "",
  "3.8 V, 12 times the current capacity": "",
  "15.2 V, same current capacity as one cell": "",
  "45.6 V, same current capacity as one cell": "",
  "Four cells in series: 4 x 3.8 = 15.2 V. Three parallel strings: voltage stays 15.2 V, but current capacity triples (each parallel string adds its capacity). Series connections add voltage; parallel connections add current capacity. This is how battery packs for electric vehicles and laptops are designed.": ""
}